•PASSIVE COMMUNICATION is a style in which individuals have developed a pattern of avoiding expressing their opinions or feelings, protecting their rights, and identifying and meeting their needs. As a result, passive individuals do not respond overtly to hurtful or anger-inducing situations.

•For many with social anxiety, low self-esteem, and poor confidence leads to a passive communication style. 

• Being passive can lead to: low self-esteem, unhealthy or uncomfortable relationships, feeling out of control of decisions, and feelings of anxiety, stress, resentment or tension.

⁉️How do you stop being this way?

Learn to be more assertive
Assess your style. Do you voice your opinions or remain silent? ...
Use ‘I’ statements. Using I statements lets others know what you’re thinking or feeling without sounding accusatory. ...
Practice saying NO. ...
Rehearse what you want to say(I write notes) 
Use body language. ...
Keep emotions in check. ...
Start small.

It’s just as important if not more to learn your style of communication, so you can teach others how to treat you, and likewise learning those of who you’re in relationship with. 

🎧Thoughts from my last episode of THINKING OUT LOUD PODCAST that will be available this Thursday 12/15/22 on Apple.

I LOVE me a good stretch in the morning & night. Be INTENTIONAL about it* I spend 15 mins on the floor( back, legs, pelvis, toes, abdomen) & 15 mins standing (neck, arms, hands, fingers , shoulders, waist) in silence … simply following my breath; inhale through the nose and exhale slowly out through your mouth.. with the intention to not only slow down my heart rate but slow down PERIOD. Take a break! It’s absolutely okay and NECESSARY to be STILL with you. This healing journey for me has been so enlightening, heartfelt and empowering. I believe in medicine but I also believe the power of the MIND. I AM. I CAN & I WILL. Others like to question and seek logic, for me I have learned to let go and just TRUST. What is, IS, and what will be, will always work out for the greater good; my BELIEF. The mind is a very powerful thing and so be careful with the words you feed it and who you allow into your mental space…. Anyway here’s your daily reminder to BREATHE. Be grateful for breath, some can’t do what you do naturally, embrace your power 🙌🏽🤍🤎

⚠️TRIGGER WARNING⚠️ my ❤️‍🩹 goes out to all the women who have suffered 👼 loss.

2022 for me, was by far the worse year of my entire life. What I can take from the year is that my strength is truly impeccable. And despite of everything I endured so many women poured into me, shared their pregnancy news with me because they knew that despite of.. I would be GENUINELY happy for them. A baby is truly a blessing 🙏🏽 I’m thankful and privileged to be trusted with such great news. I’m thankful that despite of, people leaned on me for support through hardships because they saw my strength, despite of. I’m thankful that despite of, I was still able to help so many people on their wellness journey. 

I was recently diagnosed with Tumid Lupus LE, which is why I haven’t been able to carry a pregnancy because my body is always in chronic pain, but with that, I have awareness and knowledge and can soon start treatment to heal, and move forward. 

With all the hardships that comes with this, the good is being to able to help other people: I’ve been able to connect to hundreds of people and build such an amazing community on social media, despite it being so hard at times, it’s my vulnerability, my transparency, my courage that has not only help to heal me, but others. It allowed others to open up and share their stories and begin the process of healing too. 

My journey is far beyond me, my purpose is greater than me, and I’ll be forever stepping into it with more lessons to pass forward. 

I let go of so much hurt, pain, anxiety, my fertility journey, the depression 2022 has brought me, with the loss of my 3 Angel babies and the relationship attached. 

2023 I welcome abundance, nothing but HEALING, happiness, peace, LOVE, loyalty and laughter for the soul 🤍 

I deserve to glow again, and so do you. 

#lettinggo 
#healingjourney
#2022recap 
#newblessings

#morelife
That’s it 🤞🏽

The thing about healing is that emotions comes in waves and that’s absolutely normal. When you feel good embrace it; turn to gratitude & be thankful for how you feel, what your body can do, and be in that energy, that’s your free will. That’s you owning your power. We don’t have to claim our emotions as fact or permanent. It can absolutely be and most of the time is, a temporary feeling. Focusing on the facts of you knowing and owning your own strength and deciding to step into the power and energy more good days will come. 

Easier said than done, yes, but start small and exactly where you’re at. No gym, no plan for 30 days, just now, and the rest will follow. Just focus on WHY you’re doing it vs HOW am I gonna go it.

Our journey started September 2021 when we decided to intentionally try for baby #2; we successfully became pregnant by November 2021, and sadly miscarried January 2022. We then continued to try April 2022, and fell pregnant again December 2022, and it shortly ended that same month. January 2023, we decided to try ONE last time and with good faith, intentions, much more educated, patient, and when we truly let go, and allowed God we fell pregnant again.

Now further along than the last two pregnancies, baby is strong! Momma is strong & daddy is still with high hopes, and big sis is super excited 🥰

🌈 In my fertility journey I learned to practice “Mindfulness” and what it really meant. You can easily become so frustrated, disappointed, loss of hope in the waiting, but learning to simply stop and just be aware of not only what’s going on with me and around me, made all the difference in my perspective.

•When people think of mindfulness, they often mistake it for clearing your thoughts and doing nothing, but it’s really about being aware of what’s happening around you without attaching any judgment to it and accepting things as they are. 

•It can be as simple as paying full attention to what you see and hear, and just doing that helped me reduce my anxiety, depression, and general irritability.

•We’re constantly doing multiple things at once, so it can be really helpful for people to practice slowing down and doing one thing at a time, with awareness.

•Being present and appreciating what’s right in front of you can be a powerful act and doesn’t have to take much time out of your day.

☀️This daily practice allowed me to trust myself, time, my body, and not attaching my emotions to any outcomes and just accepting them as apart of my journey, Total mind shift 🙌🏽

It’s hard to be pregnant with another kid at home.⁣⁣

⁣⁣
⁣
And no one else is going to clean the house and tackle that huge pile of laundry because your joints hurt, and your ankles are swollen,⁣⁣
or bathe your kid/ kids because you feel so much pressure in your nether regions.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⁣
And no one’s taking care of ALL THE THINGS for you, so you’re spending most of the day on your feet: running around, and keeping up with yours and her schedule.
⁣
But you’re not alone,⁣⁣
every part of mothering becomes harder when you’re pregnant: mentally and physically.⁣⁣
 ⁣⁣
⁣
Because both pregnancy and parenting are hard work, so when combined, it can feel like you’re doing everything wrong at times.⁣⁣
 ⁣⁣
⁣
But give yourself grace.⁣⁣
 ⁣⁣
⁣
Because it’s okay to put your child / children in front of a screen so you can take a midday nap.⁣⁣
It’s okay to give them mini muffins as you rush them out the door for school because you overslept.⁣⁣
 ⁣⁣
⁣
Plus, your children won’t remember what you didn’t do during this time.⁣⁣
 ⁣⁣
⁣
They’ll only remember you loving them,⁣⁣
trying,⁣⁣
and showing up—⁣⁣
and that’s what matters most,⁣⁣
through every stage of motherhood. ⁣⁣

🗯️Did you know a birthing ball can help you to drop the baby in pelvis, positioning the baby, relieving back pain and aiding in labor.

Start at 32 weeks, the birthing ball exercises help you prepare for labor-
•by opening pelvis, 
•helping in dropping baby into pelvis
•getting baby in an optimal position for birth 
•strengthening your pelvic floor and back:

🌟Use these 5 ball exercises and get ready to meet your baby. 

1. Bouncing- Allows your pelvis to remain open and help in dropping the baby in pelvis.
3.  Pelvic tilts- Back and Forth-Effective way to encourage dilation and keep your pelvis open.
4. Side lunges with wide open legs-stretch the muscles of pelvic floor and allows baby to descend.
5. Hip Circle-Help baby move through the pelvis and help in taking optimal position for birth. Do right & left.
6. Alternative pelvic tilt while resting on the ball and rest-Help in relieving back pain and strengthening the pelvic floor muscles.

‼️You can do most of them by leaning on chair if a birthing ball is not available.

💭 Remember, check with your Gynecologist before attempting these exercises.

Postpartum is the hardest part of pregnancy. This is the 4th trimester business that’s not talked about often. This is when moms need more support than ever with:

📌getting around the house (especially after a C-section), 📌showering, 
📌helping with older kids (if any), 
📌bringing over cooked dinner or take out so it’s one less thing for mom to think about, 
📌pick up any accumulating house chores so she’s not sitting in clutter
📣 (cleanliness really helps keep her mind on baby and herself and reduces the risk of postpartum depression)
📌 helping get reorganized after unpacking from the hospital stay
📌and the biggest one, looking after baby while she catches up on sleep after a bi-hourly night feeding shift.
📣reducing exhaustion helps keep her mental health high and her mood will significantly improve with better sleep. 

📌📌📌This is NOT a time for you to come over and snuggle baby while mom does all the things. Don’t expect to be entertained. Don’t expect an invite over during one of the most critical trimesters in her life , especially if you haven’t shown her she can count on your SUPPORT while she was pregnant. 

And mostly, DON’T BE OFFENDED DURING THIS SEASON WHILE MOM IS PRESERVING HERSELF AND EMBARKING ON A NEW TRIMESTER. 🧡

Offer help. Be kind. Adjust with her.

Self-care is crucial for new mothers, especially those who experience #PPD. Taking care of yourself can help prevent and manage PPD by reducing stress, improving mood, and promoting overall well being. Self-care also allows you to recharge and replenish your energy, which is essential when taking care of a newborn.
So, what does self-care look like for new mothers? 

It can be as simple as taking a few minutes every day to do something that makes you feel good, such as taking a long shower, reading a book, or listening to music. Self-care can also involve more significant changes, such as delegating tasks, asking for help, setting boundaries, and making time for exercise, healthy eating, and SLEEPING.

Second time around I’m making sure to get dressed, do my hair, stick to a routine (as much as possible) and continue to put me first; it’s NOT selfish it’s necessary. If I’m not good, then no one around me will be.

Babies gestate for 9 months OUTSIDE the womb: Human babies are born incredibly immature compared to most mammals. The reason for this is that babies complete an “ex gestational” period, where they rely on their mothers to regulate their breathing, temperature, stress levels, and nervous system for about 9 months. Babies do not realize they are physically separate from their mother until 9 months old.

Next time you hear someone say “you’re spoiling them” because you’re holding them “too much” ignore it, educate them, or continue to follow your intuition, it’s not wrong, they are.

3 weeks exclusively breastfeeding the second time around and feels like the very first!

He’s what I’ve learned since I last breastfed 10 years ago⬇️

•Your body works on supply & demand: it’ll produce exactly what your baby needs (can be tricky in the beginning when you first nurse your baby and can’t see how much they’re drinking) you wonder if it’s enough, it is! Their stomachs are SUPER TINY and those first few drops are all they need.

•The first week is the toughest! My nipples definitely cracked (I used Mommas organic nipple butter) that helped to heal them.

•Breastfeeding more often: it gives your breasts the signal to produce more milk & reduce nipple pain.

•Supplement with vitamin D, pediatrics recommends giving exclusively or partially breastfed babies a vitamin D. I add hers once a day to her milk.

•If bottle feeding (ensure they have the same suction) so they don’t get confused or refuse one or the other. I do both, because it gives me room to breathe + allows her father, sister and grandparents to also feed & bond with her.

➡️Last but not least, it’s a 24/7 job; LITERALLY 24 hours around the clock nursing but so WORTH IT. It gives me a sense of empowerment & confidence knowing I’m giving my baby the best nutrients, while also motivating me to eat as clean as possible.

🤍BTW: my milk tastes like sweet almond milk: yes I tried it, so did Kaydence & my fam 🙃😌
